3.grep/egrep

  --> WHAT IS GREP ?
       -> The grep command stands for "global regular expression print."process text line by line and prints any lines which match a
  specified pattern,Basically it is specific keyword to search.

   1) grep --version OR grep --help             ==  Check version or help
   2) grep keyword(EX-:seinfeld) file           ==  search for a keyword from a file
   3) grep -c keyword file                      ==  search for a keyword and count 
   4) grep -i keyword file                      ==  search for a keyword ignore case-sensitive
   5) grep -n keyword file                      ==  Displays the matched lines amd their line numbers
   6) grep -v keyword filename                  ==  Displays everything except keyword
   7) grep keyword filename | awk '{print} $1'  ==  search for a keyword and then only gives 1st field
   8) ls -l | grep Desktop                      ==  search for a keyword and then only give the 1st filed
   

  --> egrep

     1) egrep -i "keyword|keyword" filename     ==  search for 2 keywords.
